## Step 6: Add and Commit Files

```bash
# Stage all files
git add .

# Verify files are staged
git status

# Commit with message
git commit -m "Initial commit: iPad A2316 reset guides (Windows + Linux)"
```

**Expected output:** Lists all files being committed.

---

## Step 7: Link to GitHub Remote

```bash
# Rename default branch to main
git branch -M main

# Add GitHub remote
git remote add origin https://github.com/yourname/ipad-a2316-reset.git

# Verify remote
git remote -v
```

Should show:
```
origin  https://github.com/yourname/ipad-a2316-reset.git (fetch)
origin  https://github.com/yourname/ipad-a2316-reset.git (push)
```

---

## Step 8: Push to GitHub

```bash
git push -u origin main
```

**First time:** GitHub will ask for authentication

**Options:**
- **HTTPS:** Enter GitHub username + Personal Access Token (easier)
- **SSH:** Use SSH key pair (more secure, requires setup)

### If using HTTPS:

1. Generate Personal Access Token on GitHub:
   - Settings â†’ Developer settings â†’ Personal access tokens â†’ Tokens (classic)
   - Click **Generate new token (classic)**
   - Check `repo` scope
   - Copy token (save it, you'll only see it once)

2. At the prompt, enter:
   - **Username:** your GitHub username
   - **Password:** Paste the token (not your actual GitHub password)

### If using SSH (recommended):

```bash
# Generate SSH key (if you don't have one)
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your-email@example.com"

# Add public key to GitHub:
# Settings â†’ SSH and GPG keys â†’ New SSH key
# Paste content of ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub

# Then set remote as SSH:
git remote set-url origin git@github.com:yourname/ipad-a2316-reset.git

# Test connection
ssh -T git@github.com
```

